  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 12.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Our",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "fathers provoked the God of heaven unto wrath",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Mainly by their long series of idolatries, with the moral abominations that those idolatries involved - the sacrifice of children by their own parents, the licentious rites belonging to the worship of Baal, and the unmentionable horrors practised by the devotees of the Dea Syra. For centuries, with only short and rare intervals, \"the chief of the priests, and the people, had transgressed very much after ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "all",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the abominations of the heathen,\" and had even \"polluted the house of the Lord which he had hallowed in Jerusalem\" (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 36:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Therefore, he gave them into the hand of Nebuchadnezzar the king of Babylon",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". He punished, as he always does, national apostasy with national destruction. Making an idolatrous people, but a less guilty one, his sword, he cut off Judah, as he had previously cut off Israel, causing the national life to cease, and even removing the bulk of the people into a distant country. Not by his own power or might did Nebuchadnezzar prevail. God could have delivered the Jews from him as easily as he had delivered them in former days from Jabin (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 4:2-24",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and from Zerah (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 14:11-15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and from Sennacherib (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 19:20-36",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). But he was otherwise minded; he \"",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "gave them into the hand",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " of Nebuchadnezzar\" (comp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 36:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). He divided their counsels, paralysed their resistance, caused Pharaoh Hophra to desert their cause (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 24:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and left them helpless and unprotected. Nebuchadnczzar was his instrument to chastise his guilty people, and in pursuing his own ends merely worked out the purposes of the Almighty. Ezra 5:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "For this reason (להן), because (מן־דּי  equals  מאשׁר, e.g., ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 43:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") our fathers provoked the God of heaven, He gave them into the hand of Nebuchadnezzar king of Babylon, the Chaldean, and he (Nebuch.) destroyed this house, and carried the people away into Babylon. For כּסדּיא the Keri requires כּסדּאה, the ordinary form of the absolute state of the noun in ai. סתר, Pael, in the sense of destroy, appears only here in biblical Chaldee, but more frequently in the Targums. עמּה, its people, would refer to the town of Jerusalem; but Norzi and J. H. Mich. have עמּהּ, and the Masora expressly says that the word is to be written without Mappik, and is therefore the stat. emphat. for עמּא. ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]